## About the AP Exam

##### Our CS Principles curriculum prepares students for the multiple-choice exam and Create Performance Task components of the AP Exam. We've worked to ensure the curriculum is mapped to <a href="https://www.csteachers.org/page/standards" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CSTA standards</a> and aligns with the College Board's five "Big Ideas" and six "Computational Thinking Practices" outlined in their <a href="https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/pdf/ap-computer-science-principles-conceptual-framework-2020-21.pdf" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">AP CS Principles Conceptual Framework</a>: 

<img src="https://images.code.org/e5310c7c4b9e2f3f749352839a70dc86-image-1653430250056.10.41 PM.png" align="center" alt="Table including the five Big Ideas and six Computational Thinking Practices. The Big Ideas are Creative Development, Data, Algorithms and Programming, Computer Systems & Networks, and Impact of Computing. The Computational Thinking Practices are Computational Solution Design, Algorithms and Program Development, Abstraction in Program Development, Code Analysis, Computing Innovations, and Responsible Computing.">

##### More specific information about the CS Principles AP Exam is available in **Module 3: Overview of CS Principles**, including what is covered in the multiple-choice exam and Create Performance Task, as well as how to set your class up to take the exam.
